<article>
    <h1>Here&#x2019;s to the S&#x2019;pore spirit</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200809/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-09"><time>2020-08-09</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline">An&#xAD;jali Ragu&#xAD;ra&#xAD;man&#xD;&#xA;Toast to Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore&#x2019;s birthday with newly re&#xAD;leased beers and spe&#xAD;cially con&#xAD;cocted cock&#xAD;tails made with uniquely lo&#xAD;cal flavours like on&#xAD;deh on&#xAD;deh and or&#xAD;chid. an&#xAD;jalir@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>SPICESUTRA: WALK­ING THE SPICE ROUTES OF IN­DIA</p>
    <p>What: Cook­ing laksa with In­dian spices? Chef Man­ju­nath Mu­ral (above, left) of one-Miche­lin­starred restau­rant The Song of In­dia and chef Deep­anker Khosla (above, right) of sus­tain­able fine-din­ing restau­rant Haoma in Thai­land come to­gether in this class and put their own spin on the pop­u­lar lo­cal favourite, us­ing in­gre­di­ents found in Sin­ga­pore and Thai­land.</p>
    <p>When: Aug 29, 7pm</p>
    <p>HOLYCRAB: SUP­PER TREATS</p>
    <p>What: It is all about the “woke” hei in chef El­ton Seah’s dishes from HolyCrab restau­rant in Tan Quee Lan Street. His mas­ter­class is an ex­po­si­tion on how to coat pip­ing hot stir-fries with that be­guil­ing charred aroma, or breath of the wok.</p>
    <p>His in­gre­di­ent box, priced at $120, fea­tures three dishes – umami har cheong deep-fried pork belly (above), Can­tonese pan-fried cod with ginger scal­lions, and savoury wok-fried por­ridge with cod. Food bun­dles are priced from $52.90.</p>
    <p>When: Aug 21, 9.30pm</p>
    <p>OF DURIAN AND BLUE CHEESE: A TAST­ING JOUR­NEY</p>
    <p>What: Find out all about the king of fruits – from the har­vest­ing process to dif­fer­ent flavours among the durian va­ri­etals – in this col­lab­o­ra­tion be­tween Chef Chung Dem­ing of The Quar­ters restau­rant and durian seller Durian Edi­tion.</p>
    <p>Com­plete the ex­pe­ri­ence with the durian tast­ing pack ($36), which in­cludes Mao Shan Wang and D24 vari­ants, and durian kaya.</p>
    <p>Par­tic­i­pants will also learn how to make durian cream – per­fect for pas­tries – with durian flesh, su­gar and cook­ing cream, which are also in­cluded in the pack.</p>
    <p>When: Aug 22, 2.30pm</p>
    <p>Tiger Or­chid Brew by Tiger Beer</p>
    <p>Sin­ga­pore’s very own Tiger Beer has re­leased a lim­ited- edi­tion black lager in­fused with Tiger or­chids that im­part sub­tle flo­ral notes.</p>
    <p>First re­leased as a sea­sonal beer to mark the launch of the Tiger Street Lab at Jewel Changi Air­port in April last year, the beer is now avail­able is­land­wide till the end of the month.</p>
    <p>The strik­ing blue-and-pur­ple can de­picts the hardy or­chid flower, and is de­signed by Sin­ga­porean artist and il­lus­tra­tor Tif­fany Lo­vage.</p>
    <p>Price: $11.70 for a four-can pack</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: Ma­jor su­per­mar­kets, con­ve­nience stores and online mar­ket­places like Lazada</p>
    <p>Gar­den City Ne­groni by Nutmeg & Clove and Roketto Iza­kaya</p>
    <p>Cock­tail bar Nutmeg & Clove has part­nered Chef Willin Low of Wild Rocket and Roketto Iza­kaya to cre­ate a cock­tail named af­ter Sin­ga­pore’s Gar­den City vi­sion that was first pro­posed in the 1960s.</p>
    <p>Lo­cal in­gre­di­ents flavour this flo­ral spin on the clas­sic ne­groni, which is made with ginger flower-in­fused Hen­drick’s Gin, cu­cum­ber and rose ver­mouth and ly­chee vine­gar.</p>
    <p>Only 55 bot­tles are avail­able for sale dur­ing the Na­tional Day pe­riod. Each pur­chase comes with a voucher for a com­pli­men­tary dessert and cock­tail pair­ing at Roketto Iza­kaya at Frasers Tower.</p>
    <p>Price: $65 for a 250ml bot­tle</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: www.nut­meg­clove.com</p>
    <p>Info: What­sApp 8245-9262 for in­quiries</p>
    <p>Straits Set by Com­pendium</p>
    <p>Small-batch spir­its and mead pro­ducer Com­pendium – the peo­ple be­hind the Chen­dol and Ro­jak gins re­leased last year – con­tinue to go lo­cal.</p>
    <p>In­stead of pota­toes or ce­real, the Straits Vodka is dis­tilled from mead made from South-east Asian wild­flower honey, com­bined with re­gion­ally for­aged nutmeg and cin­na­mon.</p>
    <p>While ar­rack – a spirit orig­i­nat­ing from South and South-east Asia – is typ­i­cally dis­tilled from co­conut or palm sap, Com­pendium makes its ver­sion by dou­ble-dis­till­ing slow-fer­mented gula me­laka in­stead.</p>
    <p>Price: $98 for a Straits Set – Straits Vodka (250ml) and Me­laka Ar­rack (250ml)</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: rachel­lether­ab­bit.com</p>
    <p>Neslo Gao Peng and Salty Egg-cep­tional bot­tled cock­tails by GudSht</p>
    <p>Al­co­hol de­liv­ery out­fit and bot­tled cock­tail ex­pert GudSht has re­leased two lim­ited-edi­tion, uniquely Sin­ga­porean con­coc­tions, which are avail­able till the end of the month.</p>
    <p>One is a riff on the clas­sic cof­fee-shop bev­er­age, Neslo (Nescafe and Milo), and the other cel­e­brates the Sin­ga­porean ob­ses­sion with salted egg.</p>
    <p>Neslo Gao Peng is made with Haku vodka, white ca­cao, freshly brewed cof­fee, fresh honey, Milo and An­gos­tura bit­ters; while Salty Egg-cep­tional is stirred up with Bac­ardi Carta Ne­gra, house­made cin­na­mon syrup and salted egg.</p>
    <p>GudSht also has sev­eral cock­tails in­spired by lo­cal favourites, such as Kaya, I Beg Your Pan­dan ($50 for 600ml) – a rum-based drink in­spired by kaya toast and kopi – and Cheng Tng Gao, made with freshly boiled cheng tng and cognac ($36 for 600ml).</p>
    <p>Price: $33 (300ml) or $55 (600ml)</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: www.gudsht.org</p>
    <p>Scar­let 55 by Man­hat­tan</p>
    <p>To cel­e­brate Sin­ga­pore’s birthday and cham­pion a lo­cally made spirit, award-win­ning cock­tail bar Man­hat­tan at Re­gent Sin­ga­pore has con­cocted a red-hued take on a ne­groni.</p>
    <p>It is made with Sin­ga­pore Dry Gin from home-grown dis­tillery Brass Lion, Mar­tini Bit­ter, Mar­tini Secco and Man­darine Napoleon liqueur for a cit­rus, herb and spice fin­ish. Price: $24 for a 100ml bot­tle</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: Take­away booth at Re­gent Sin­ga­pore. Or­der at bit.ly/3keLu5X for col­lec­tion or home de­liv­ery</p>
    <p>Info: For in­quiries, e-mail tak­ere­gen­thome@ re­gentsin­ga­pore.com.sg or call 6725-3057</p>
    <p>On­deh On­deh Porter by Sun­bird Brew­ing</p>
    <p>Lo­cal mi­cro­brew­ery Sun­bird Brew­ing, a new ad­di­tion to the craft beer brew­ing scene, got the in­spi­ra­tion for its first sea­sonal brew from one of head brewer Clive Tan’s favourite child­hood snacks – on­deh on­deh.</p>
    <p>The porter was brewed with gula me­laka, co­conut and pan­dan, re­sult­ing in co­conut notes on the nose and the dis­tinct roasted malt flavour of a porter on the fin­ish.</p>
    <p>Launched in April, the mi­cro­brew­ery in Mandai also has four core beers – a pale ale, white In­dia Pale Ale, Scot­tish Ale and Bel­gian Wit­bier.</p>
    <p>Price: $55 for a six-bot­tle pack Info: www.sun­bird­brew­ingco.com</p>
    <p>Day In Au­gust by Brew­lan­der and Alive Brew­ing Co</p>
    <p>Es­tab­lished home-grown brew­ery Brew­lan­der has teamed up with new kid on the block Alive Brew­ing Co for a kaf­fir lime wit­bier called Day In Au­gust.</p>
    <p>Brim­ming with trop­i­cal fruit flavours and lifted by kaf­fir lime zest with a black pep­per fin­ish, the re­fresh­ing beer was brewed with Kveik, a hardy Nor­we­gian yeast strain that is gain­ing pop­u­lar­ity among con­tem­po­rary brew­ers.</p>
    <p>Like farm­house-style beers that use in­gre­di­ents read­ily avail­able at the time, the beer has added spices and in­gre­di­ents used in ev­ery­day Sin­ga­pore dishes such as black pep­per, kaf­fir lime and co­rian­der seeds.</p>
    <p>Price: $7 a bot­tle</p>
    <p>Avail­able at: www.brew­lan­der.com and www.alive­brew­ing.co</p>

